history.content:
You should be fine. Here are some gaps that you can fill if you want to be more prepared:

- Proofs (direct, contraposition, contradiction, and arguably most importantly induction)

Go to sp17.eecs70.org and read Notes 2 + 3.

- Basic Probability

Go to sp17.eecs70.org and read Notes 12 + 13. Then do http://practice.eecs70.org/#/set/8.

- Partial Derivatives

If you are taking MATH53 next semester, read the sections on partial derivatives (just know how to take them) and double integrals (how to set up and evaluate). Then, if you understand section 15.5 Applications of Double Integrals, you will feel really, really good near the end of the semester.

children.subject: Projections are covered really early on in MATH 53 which I think is the only relevant part of 54 that is really needed for the regressions.

MATH 53 does not cover vector space. I think the only part MATH 53 relevant to CS 70 is partial derivatives and double integral, which is somewhat useful for understanding the joint distribution of continuous probability, but these knowledge are really easy to self-learn.
I think MATH 54 is helpful for understanding the regression part.

history.content: I have read on some posts that it is not enough to take CS 70 after only Math 1b. Can someone who has taken CS 70 without having taken Math 54/EE16A/B share how they felt with CS 70 with only Math 1B knowledge?
